vectorData.altText: 25. What action is associated with tendons that cross the inferior aspect of the toes?
That's right!  Tendons that cross the inferior aspect of the toes cause flexion.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
REMOVE your shoes and socks, and follow along.

It will help if you think of your hands as feet; hold your hands palms down and the dorsum of the hand facing upward. Your palms are analogous to the soles (inferior surface) of your feet and the dorsum of your hand is analogous to the dorsum (superior surface) of your feet.

Tendons that pull along the inferior surface of the toes (red arrow) cause them to curl under. Keep in mind that the sole of the foot is analogous to the palm of the hand     . What movement occurs at the MTP    , PIP and DIP joints of the toes? Think, then click:

Tendons that pull along the superior surface of the toes (green arrow) cause them to turn upwards. Keep in mind that the dorsum of the foot is analogous to the dorsum of the hand. What movement occurs at the MCP, PIP and DIP joints of the toes? Think, then click:

The toes are capable of abduction and adduction at the MTP joints, just as the fingers are capable of abduction and adduction at the MCP joints. As in the hands, this movement pair is carried out by intrinsic muscles of the feet. You will not be taught about the abductors and adductors of the toes.
